The German phrase "Europäische Verteidigung und Europäische Solidarität" translates to "European Defense and European Solidarity" in English.
PRAG: Maybe it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
It might be due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that for centuries has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and European confrontations.
Perhaps all these factors, combined, have led me to come to the conviction that Europe represents a single political unity whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be forever two Europes  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, the other less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is a mistake.
This is like being able to heat up one part of a room while the other part remains cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event resonates throughout Europe.
If Europe is to become unified, and if the European Union is to welcome the new post-communist democracies – which is in Europe's interest – a series of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must foster community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe thus must help its new democracies become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more they are interconnected, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership, and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer diverse solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and nonprofit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economical it will become; and the better it will be at satisfying those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their organizations.
Authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that can only be exercised by states.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its abandonment of European solidarity, which led to the capitulation at Munich.
This experience is still a vigorous call for vigilance.
One must confront the evil as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if governments act alone.
Because government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern about security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept for its security policy.
It should stand out through its ability to make quick decisions and to implement communal decisions swiftly – reforms that the most recent developments in Yugoslavia have shown to be necessary.
The intervention of NATO last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the interests of pan-European security, requires interventions beyond the EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations in which the UN mandate might not be obtained, even though an intervention would be in the interest of many people, indeed of Europe as a whole, and even of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better equipped, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be utilized to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
However, more is needed in the field of preventive security, but it is also necessary to ensure that this security reflects the values of Europe's extended civil society.
Tens of thousands of lives and enormous amounts of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflict.
Despite warnings about impending horror, people only acted timidly.
These delays were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be witnessing the atrocities in Kosovo.
Europe cannot be permanently dependent on the USA, especially regarding European problems.
It must be able to communicate with solutions on its own.
It is inconceivable that the EU can remain a respected part of the world order if it fails to find ways and means to protect human rights, not only on its own territory but also in regions that may join it in the future.
Such an EU expansion is only conceivable if it proceeds hand in hand with a bold reform of EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the government conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals for advancing the union.
But I consider this as the beginning of a process that might take decades and should be guided by a sustained effort to accelerate and make the EU decision-making more transparent.
A point related to institutional reform is how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not be simply overridden by the larger ones, while still appropriately taking into account the size of individual states.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would be elected not directly, but by the parliaments of the member states from their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU – i.e., the current Parliament – would therefore reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber, with the same number of representatives for each state, would increase equality.
At some point in the future, these changes will require the EU to have a clear and understandable constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and obligations of both European citizens and the states, the underlying values, and the significance and objectives of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships to each other.
Such a constitution would not entail an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal overstate that euroskeptics fear.
However, it would help the citizens of a integrated Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to better understand it, to see the relevance of the EU for their lives, and consequently, to identify with it.
